{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4a719f64-5a93-43e7-afa9-a13313baaea5","content":"The working directory is empty, so I'll answer from general .NET/macOS knowledge.\n\nOn macOS, when `createdump` isn't available (common with NativeAOT since it's not bundled), you can recover a crash dump using the **macOS system crash reporter**:\n\n1. **Enable core dumps** — run `ulimit -c unlimited` before launching your app.\n\n2. **Check for macOS crash reports** — the system crash reporter writes logs to:\n   - `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`\n   - `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`\n\n   Look for files matching your process name.\n\n3. **Get a core file via `lldb`** — attach to or launch the process under `lldb`:\n   ```\n   lldb ./MyApp\n   run\n   # after crash:\n   process save-core myapp.core\n   ```\n\n4. **Use `/cores/` directory** — if core dumps are enabled (`ulimit -c unlimited`) and `/cores/` exists with write permissions, macOS writes core files there (e.g., `/cores/core.<pid>`).\n\n5. **Analyze with `lldb`**:\n   ```\n   lldb --core /cores/core.12345 ./MyApp\n   bt   # backtrace\n   ```\n\n> **Tip:** On Apple Silicon, you may also need to disable SIP or codesign your binary with the `get-task-allow` entitlement for core dumps to be written.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"850949b0-1132-434b-9ccb-2427d277910b","outputTokens":352,"requestId":"9813:208367:BAE8EF:DB8AF7:69F406D1"},"id":"bdbc7eff-bb3d-4c03-a18f-2cb1601dcab8","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:50:41.447Z","parentId":"441a8dc9-ae48-442b-a626-2e13ffdd2e72"}
